 tChapter 12. Sovereign Wealth Funds and Long-Term Investments in Infrastructure: Why the Glaring Absence? -- tChapter 13. North America’s Sovereign Wealth Funds: Origins, Models, and Lessons -- tChapter 14. Sovereign Venture Funds: An Emerging Frontier in Sovereign Wealth Fund Management -- tChapter 15. Conclusion -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSovereign wealth funds (SWFs) can be effective tools for national resources revenue management. These state-owned investments, funded by commodity exports, foreign exchange reserves, or other national assets, are adaptable to the challenges posed by financial shocks and have been successfully employed in an increasing number of countries. The number of SWFs continues to grow, with the largest funds managing trillions of dollars in assets among them. However, given the significant variations among SWFs, it can be difficult to compare funds that differ in size, scope, and mandate. This book provides a sorely needed practical look at how these funds work—and how they should work.The New Frontiers of Sovereign Investment combines the insights and experience of academic economists and practitioners from several funds to survey a diverse financial landscape and establish the challenging topical questions facing a broad range of SWFs today: Should they serve both economic development and financial returns, and how? Will responsible investment enhance long-term returns? How can fiscal rules for SWFs be improved to meet emerging economic challenges? The book considers these questions as they apply to both long-established and newer SWFs. Featuring contributions from sovereign wealth practitioners from Alberta's AIMCo, the Nigerian Sovereign Investment Authority, and the New Zealand Superannuation Fund, as well as analysis by scholars at the forefront of sovereign investment, this volume provides timely and much-needed information on these rapidly evolving institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aInvestment of public funds. 0aSovereign wealth funds. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / Economic Development.2bisacsh1 aAnasashvili, Nikoloz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauer, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeléchat, Corinne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDixon, Adam D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGelb, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGratcheva, Ekaterina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalland, Håvard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMonk, Ashby H. B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOhrenstein, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOjekwe-Onyejeli, Stella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrji, Uche, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrr, Adrian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOteh, Arunma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeters, Sanjay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRietveld, Malan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRietveld, Malan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSantiso, Javier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchneider, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToledano, Perrine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToledano, Perrine, eedit